        <p>
            You've read the theory. You understand ethos, pathos, and logos. You can steelman an opponent's position, recognize a fallacy at twenty paces, and time your arguments for maximum impact. Now you want to test yourself against real opponents, in real time, with real stakes.
        </p>

        <p>
            Welcome to competitive online debate. Specifically: SuperDebate.org, where the principles of this book meet the pressures of the arena. This appendix won't teach you new rhetoric—everything you need is in the preceding twenty chapters. What it will teach you is how to deploy that rhetoric under the specific constraints of structured platform competition.
        </p>

        <p>
            The Greeks trained in gymnasiums before competing in the games. Consider this your pre-competition briefing.
        </p>

        <h2>THE PLATFORM: WHAT YOU'RE WALKING INTO</h2>

        <p>
            SuperDebate is structured online debate. Unlike Twitter arguments or Reddit threads—where anyone can jump in, threads fork infinitely, and there's no resolution—SuperDebate has rules, turns, time limits, and judges. This changes everything.
        </p>

        <p>
            The format matters. You'll have a set time for your opening case, a set time to respond, a set time for cross-examination. When time expires, you stop. No "just one more point." No "but I didn't get to say..." This constraint is liberating once you accept it. You can't say everything, so you must say what matters most.
        </p>

        <p>
            The audience matters differently here than in casual argument. In SuperDebate, you're addressing three distinct groups simultaneously: the judge who will render a decision, the opponent who will respond to your arguments, and the spectators who will watch and learn. Each audience requires slightly different calibration—but the judge is primary. Persuading spectators while losing the judge's ballot is a bad trade.
        </p>

        <div class="vocabulary-box">
            <span class="vocab-term">Flow</span>
            <span class="vocab-pronunciation">FLOW</span>
            <p class="vocab-definition">The debater's shorthand for tracking arguments in real time. A flow is a written record of each argument made, each response given, and each dropped point. Skilled debaters flow automatically, creating a map of the debate as it unfolds. The name comes from the flow of arguments across columns: their case, your response, their extension, your rebuttal.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
            Reputation accumulates. Unlike anonymous social media, your SuperDebate record follows you. Every debate is archived. Past performance shapes future credibility. This means ethos compounds—good debates build a reputation that makes future judges more receptive. It also means character matters. Win ugly too often, and judges will scrutinize your arguments more harshly.
        </p>

        <p>
            Everything is on record. The permanence of online debate cuts both ways. Your brilliant arguments persist—but so do your embarrassing ones. You can't unsay what you've written. This should make you more careful, not more timid. Write arguments you'd be proud to have attributed to you in five years.
        </p>

