        <h2>TIME-PRESSURE TACTICS</h2>

        <p>
            The clock is the great equalizer. Every debater, no matter how brilliant, faces the same constraint: limited time to make unlimited arguments. Your advantage comes not from having more time, but from using time better.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Flow as you go.</strong> Don't wait until the end to figure out what happened. Keep a running record of your opponent's arguments. Number them. Note which ones you've answered. Note which ones you've dropped (consciously or not). The flow is your battle map. Without it, you're fighting blind.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Triage ruthlessly.</strong> You cannot answer every argument. Don't try. Instead, identify which arguments actually matter for the judge's decision. An opponent making twelve arguments isn't making twelve winning arguments—most are supporting evidence for a few core claims. Attack the core claims. If those fall, the evidence becomes irrelevant.
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The 10-Second Reset</div>
            <p>When you feel overwhelmed by time pressure—heart racing, thoughts scattering—take a deliberate breath. Then ask yourself one question: "What is the single most important thing I need to say?" Say that first. If time permits, say the second most important thing. This forces prioritization when your brain wants to panic.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
            <strong>Pre-load responses.</strong> Competitive debaters build mental libraries of common arguments and their counters. If someone claims "free markets always produce optimal outcomes," you shouldn't need to invent a response from scratch—you should have three or four ready to deploy, calibrated to different time windows. This isn't intellectual laziness; it's preparation. Lincoln didn't improvise the Cooper Union speech.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Practice recovery.</strong> You will get flustered. You will miss arguments. You will realize mid-sentence that you're making a mistake. The skill isn't avoiding these moments—it's recovering from them. The worst response is visible panic. The second-worst is pretending nothing happened. The best response is brief acknowledgment ("Let me reframe that—") followed by getting back on track. Judges respect poise under pressure.
        </p>

        <p>
            Time pressure rewards what the Greeks called <em>phronesis</em>: practical wisdom about what matters in a given situation. You developed phronesis in <a href="/chapters/part-2/chapter-05-ethos/">Chapter 5</a>. Now you apply it at speed.
        </p>

