        <h2>WRITTEN DEBATE RHETORIC</h2>

        <p>
            Online debate is written debate. You can't adjust your tone based on facial reactions. You can't clarify with "what I mean is..." when someone looks confused. Your words arrive without your voice, your expressions, or your presence. This creates both constraints and opportunities.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Compression, not truncation.</strong> Character limits force economy, but economy isn't the same as amputation. Don't take a 500-word argument and chop it at 280 characters. Instead, find the core claim and express it in the tightest possible form. "Free markets optimize resource allocation through price signals, but market failures exist where prices don't capture true costs—externalities make laissez-faire insufficient" is not a truncation of a longer argument. It's a compression of a book-length argument into a single deployable assertion. Practice writing your entire case in one paragraph. Then in one sentence. Then in ten words. What survives is what matters.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Formatting as emphasis.</strong> Bold text, bullet points, numbered lists—these are rhetorical devices, not just visual aids. Use them deliberately. A bulleted list signals "here are discrete items to evaluate separately." Bold signals "this is the key phrase." Overuse dilutes the effect. If everything is bold, nothing is bold.
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Headline Test</div>
            <p>Read your opening line. If it were a headline, would it be clickbait or substance? "Here's Why You're Wrong About Everything" is clickbait. "Three reasons price controls create shortages" is substance. Judges can tell the difference. Start with your actual argument, not with throat-clearing or provocation.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
            <strong>Tone calibration.</strong> Written words lack the softening effect of tone and body language. "That's wrong" reads harsher than it sounds when spoken with a thoughtful frown. This means you need to explicitly signal respect that would be implicit in person. "I disagree because..." reads better than "Wrong." This isn't weakness—it's communication competence. Remember the distinction from <a href="/chapters/part-2/chapter-06-character-in-action/">Chapter 6</a>: character demonstrated through action, not declared.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Citation matters more.</strong> In spoken debate, "studies show" might pass unchallenged in the moment. In written debate, it invites "which studies?" Link to sources. Quote precisely. Your evidence is more checkable here than in any other format—and judges who check your citations form lasting impressions about your credibility.
        </p>

