        <h2>STRATEGIC STEELMANNING</h2>

        <p>
            <a href="/chapters/part-3/chapter-15-steelmanning/">Chapter 15</a> taught steelmanning as an intellectual virtue. Here we treat it as a competitive tactic. The two aren't contradictory—virtue remains the foundation—but competitive contexts add strategic considerations.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>When to steelman:</strong> When your opponent has made a weak version of a strong argument. Rebuilding their case and then defeating it proves more than defeating their poor articulation. When you're clearly winning already and can afford generosity. When the judge values intellectual seriousness (most do). When you genuinely respect your opponent's core position even while disagreeing.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>When NOT to steelman:</strong> When time is severely limited and you need every second for your own case. When steelmanning would require making arguments your opponent explicitly declined to make. When your opponent is arguing in bad faith and steelmanning would help them more than it proves your good faith. When the charitable interpretation is so far from their stated view that it looks like you're dodging what they actually said.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                You have not converted a man because you have silenced him.
            </blockquote>
            <cite>John Morley — On Compromise, 1874</cite>
        </div>

        <p>
            <strong>The "yes, but" move.</strong> Acknowledge without agreeing. "You're right that markets create incentives for efficiency—but efficiency isn't the only value, and markets systematically ignore values that can't be priced." This demonstrates you've understood their argument (ethos), concedes a partial truth (intellectual honesty), and then pivots to your actual objection. It's stronger than pure denial and faster than full steelmanning.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Adversarial charity.</strong> The goal is to strengthen their argument and then defeat that stronger version. If you strengthen it but can't defeat it, you've made a strategic error. Before steelmanning, ask yourself: "Can I actually beat this improved version?" If not, don't improve it for them—focus on their weaker formulation.
        </p>

