        <h2>COMMON TRAPS AND COUNTERS</h2>

        <p>
            Certain tactics recur in competitive debate. Recognizing them is the first step to countering them.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The Gish Gallop.</strong> Named after creationist debater Duane Gish, this is the flood of weak arguments—too many to refute in the available time. Your opponent makes fifteen points, each requiring a paragraph to rebut. You can't rebut them all. They claim you've "dropped" fourteen arguments and win by attrition.
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>Counter:</em> Don't play their game. Explicitly name the tactic: "My opponent has offered fifteen assertions without developing any of them. I'll address the two that are actually relevant to the resolution." Then spend your time on deep engagement with the strongest points. Judges recognize the Gish Gallop and don't reward it.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The Pivot.</strong> You make an argument; they respond to a different argument. You point out a flaw; they change the subject to a strength. This slipperiness makes them hard to pin down.
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>Counter:</em> Name the move. "I argued X. My opponent responded with Y, which is a different claim. Let me return to X, which remains unaddressed." If they pivot again, note the pattern: "This is now the third time I've raised X without response." Judges track dropped arguments. Make it easy for them.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The Tone Police.</strong> Your opponent attacks your delivery rather than your argument. "That's very aggressive." "You're being dismissive." "I find that condescending." This shifts attention from what you said to how you said it.
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>Counter:</em> Brief acknowledgment, then refocus. "I apologize if my tone was unclear—let me restate the substantive point, which is..." Don't get drawn into meta-debate about civility. That's their win condition. Get back to substance.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The Appeal to Complexity.</strong> "It's more nuanced than that." "You're oversimplifying." "This issue is complicated." These phrases can be legitimate corrections—or they can be escape hatches to avoid defending an indefensible position.
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>Counter:</em> Demand specifics. "What nuance am I missing? Help me understand the specific complexity that undermines my point." If they can articulate it, engage with it. If they can't, note that "complicated" isn't an argument—it's an assertion.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The Strawman.</strong> Your argument, misrepresented. You say "we should consider alternatives"; they respond "my opponent wants to tear down the entire system."
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>Counter:</em> Correct and re-state. "That's not my position. My position is..." Then quote your original words. In written debate, this is easy—your words are right there. Let the judge see the distortion by placing the original next to the mischaracterization.
        </p>

