        <h2>BUILDING PLATFORM REPUTATION</h2>

        <p>
            Every debate you enter arrives with history. If this is your tenth debate and you've been fair, rigorous, and honest in the previous nine, judges extend goodwill. If you've been slippery, aggressive, or dishonest, they scrutinize you more closely. This is just ethos operating across time.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Consistency matters more than any single performance.</strong> One brilliant debate doesn't make a reputation. Ten good debates do. Focus on your median performance, not your peak. Eliminate your worst tendencies before trying to amplify your strengths.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Lose gracefully.</strong> When your opponent scores a genuine point, acknowledge it. "That's a fair criticism—let me respond to it directly." When you lose a debate, don't make excuses or claim the judge was biased. Say "Good debate, I learned something" and mean it. Judges talk to each other. A reputation for graciousness in defeat builds more long-term credibility than a reputation for winning while being a jerk.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The long game.</strong> The debates you lose well build more credibility than the debates you win ugly. A pyrrhic victory—achieved through technicalities, bad-faith tactics, or aggressive bullying—might give you a single win, but it costs you respect that takes dozens of good debates to rebuild. Play for the year, not the round.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                The test of a first-rate intelligence is the ability to hold two opposed ideas in the mind at the same time, and still retain the ability to function.
            </blockquote>
            <cite>F. Scott Fitzgerald — "The Crack-Up," 1936</cite>
        </div>

        <p>
            <strong>Learn the community norms.</strong> Every debate platform has its culture. SuperDebate has expectations about citation standards, argument depth, engagement quality. Watch debates before you enter them. Learn what's rewarded and what's punished. Adapt your style to the venue while keeping your substance.
        </p>

