        <h2>A BRIEF ANNOTATION</h2>

        <p>
            Let's see these principles in action. Here's a compressed exchange, with annotations:
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                <strong>Debater A:</strong> "Free markets always produce the best outcomes because they harness individual self-interest for collective good."
            </blockquote>
        </div>

        <p>
            <em>Analysis:</em> An absolute claim ("always") that's easy to attack. The warrant (self-interest → collective good) is asserted, not argued. Classic logos problem—stated conclusion without developed reasoning.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                <strong>Debater B:</strong> "My opponent is defending corporate greed that destroys communities."
            </blockquote>
        </div>

        <p>
            <em>Analysis:</em> Strawman and appeal to emotion without substance. Debater A didn't defend "greed" or "destroying communities." This is weak refutation—it scores points with people who already agree, but a judge should see through it.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                <strong>Debater A (better version):</strong> "Markets coordinate dispersed information through prices. When butter becomes scarce, rising prices signal producers to make more and consumers to use less—no central planner required. That's the mechanism."
            </blockquote>
        </div>

        <p>
            <em>Analysis:</em> Much stronger. Specific mechanism, concrete example, clear warrant. Removes the vulnerable "always" and replaces assertion with explanation.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                <strong>Debater B (better version):</strong> "I agree that prices coordinate information effectively for normal goods. But my opponent's mechanism assumes prices capture all relevant costs. With carbon emissions, the price of gas doesn't include the cost of climate damage. Markets optimize around incomplete prices—that's the market failure the resolution addresses."
            </blockquote>
        </div>

        <p>
            <em>Analysis:</em> Steelmans the mechanism argument ("I agree that prices coordinate"), then pivots to the specific limitation ("prices don't capture all costs"). Directly relevant to the resolution. Advances the debate rather than restating opening positions.
        </p>

        <p>
            Notice what the better versions have in common: specificity, concession where appropriate, direct engagement with the opponent's actual argument, and focus on the resolution rather than tangential attacks.
        </p>

