                <h4>Flow Practice</h4>
                <p>
                    Watch a recorded debate—any format, any platform. Pause after each speech and write down every argument you heard, in shorthand. Number them. After the next speech, note which arguments were addressed, which were dropped, which were extended. Review your notes: Did you catch the key claims? How did your flow compare to what actually mattered in the decision?
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="exercise">
                <span class="exercise-type">Practice</span>
                <h4>Compression Challenge</h4>
                <p>
                    Take a 500-word argument you've written (or find one in a debate). Compress it to 280 characters—a single tweet—without losing the core claim, main warrant, and impact. What did you cut? What did you keep? Now expand back to 500 words using only what you kept. Is the new version tighter than the original?
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="exercise">
                <span class="exercise-type">Challenge</span>
                <h4>Steelman Sparring</h4>
                <p>
                    Find a SuperDebate topic you personally disagree with. Write the strongest possible three-paragraph case FOR that position—as if you were assigned to defend it in a tournament. Make it genuinely persuasive. Then write your rebuttal. Did building the steelman first change how you rebut? Did you discover weaknesses in your own position?
